Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a #medium saucepan{} with a #tight-fitting lid{}. Stir in the @Basmati Rice{150%g}, @Ground Turmeric{½%sachet} and @salt{¼%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @?oil{} in a medium saucepan on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the @Korma Curry Paste{50%g}, @Tomato Puree{30%g} and garlic. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Next, pour the @Water for the Sauce{150%ml} into the pan of spices. Stir through the @Diced British Chicken Breast{260%g}, @Chicken Stock Paste{10%g}, and @Sugar{1%tsp}. Bring to a boil, then lower the heat and simmer until the chicken is cooked through and the sauce has thickened, ~{10-12%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once thickened, stir through the @Peas{120%g}, @Creme Fraiche{75%g} and @Butter{20%g}. Cook until the butter has melted and everything's piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once the rice is cooked, use a #fork{} to fluff it up. Add a splash of water to the curry if it's a little too thick. Season with salt and pepper if needed.

Share the rice between your #bowls{}. Top with the creamy butter chicken. Finish with a sprinkling of @Toasted Flaked Almonds{15%g} and @?Chilli Flakes{1%pinch} if you'd like.

> Add less chilli flakes if you'd prefer things milder.

Enjoy!